text:
(1)
Columbia Street, west side, north from but not including Grand Street, to and including Broome Street. April 4, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
A more extensive view northward. Note the Williamsburg Bridge at Delancey Street. The buildings shown in the foreground have been demolished and replaced by a modern apartment house. April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Grand Street, north side, east from Columbia Street to East River. Note the 4 hip-roofed houses (Nos. 524-530) that are just east of the 4-story building (No. 522) at the corner. These buildings are of frame construction with brick fronts. Pictures, slightly later, show No. 524 improved.

April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

At the intersection of Grand (right) and Henry (left) at Columbia Streets. The frame structure (No. 527 Grand and 327 Henry Streets), shown directly at the apex, is A.N. Gilbert's Drug Store. The Spire shown on the left, is that of All Saints Free Church (Episcopal), which is located at the S.K. corner of Henry and Scammel Streets.

April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
title: Manhattan: Grand Street - Henry Street - Columbia Street.

text:
Columbia Street, west side, north from but not including Grand, to but not including Broome Streets. Also shown (right) is Broome Street, north side, west from but not including Columbia, to but not including Willett Streets. Across the construction appears Sheriff Street, west side, north from but not including Grand, to and including Broome Streets. Building being erected on the former site of the R. Hoe and Company Printing Machine Manufacturers, will be a model slum clearance apartment house, sponsored by Governor Lehman.

June 1, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

(1)

327 and 325 Henry Street, at and adjoining its junction with Grand Street. The 3-story frame building (No. 327) at the corner also bears No. 527 Grand Street and forms the apex of the afore-mentioned junction. No. 325, the 1-story frame house is at the rear of No. 525 Grand Street; a 3-story frame house. Contiguous to it is a 1-story frame addition used as a garage which bears no number. It is at the rear of 523 Grand Street, a frame building with a rear wall made of brick. Also shown (extreme right) is No. 530 Grand Street, north
side, between Columbia and Cannon Streets.
June 6, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.
